when the local used books store has someone like that checking out manga along side children and teens who come in to look for their favorite comics. (yes, keeping my appraising eye on what manga was safe to give my children.)

My second biggest problem is when people whine that my children are reading manga at the library. They’ve gotten pretty good at that one, and usually those people either find entertainment is very square or find books to read that are appropriate to their level of maturity.

They would do well to discuss the genre in a classroom if they did not like what they saw, versus disrupting university events such as this one.

It’s not a matter of whining or liking what they see. I certainly don’t think everyone needs to check out manga (or romance novels, steampunk, fairytales, short stories, historical fiction, or whatever other genre is feminized), and I wouldn’t be surprised if some prissy people who read memoirs considered those “mundane” enough to count as “women’s stuff.” These boxes are put upon genres and then people have to conform to them. What if someone likes books about ghosts or little girl princes or something (and please check out that link! It’s quite interesting), or doesn’t fit a narrow mold of what females like and enjoy? Are they not allowed to buy into the mainstream canon because they’re a bad feminist? ESPECIALLY if these books are shaped like “brown paper bag” so people can’t
